  "output": "## Codebase reality check\n\nThis is a pure Python job-scraping pipeline (fetchers → filter → SQLite dedup → notify), not a web app — there's no React/JS anywhere in the repo, so \"unnecessary re-renders\" doesn't apply. I'll cover the four other categories with what's actually here. With 125 configured sources (`sources.yaml`) and several fetchers paginating up to 40 pages × 10-20 jobs, a single run can push tens of thousands of `Job` objects through the pipeline, which makes a couple of these findings non-trivial.\n\n### 1. N+1 query pattern — `Store.diff()` (store.py:55-74)\n\nThis is the big one. For every job in the run (potentially tens of thousands), it does a separate `SELECT`, then a separate `INSERT`/`UPDATE`:\n\n```python\nfor job in jobs:\n    row = cur.execute(\"SELECT content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key = ?\", (job.key,)).fetchone()\n    if row is None:\n        new.append(job)\n        self._insert(cur, job, now)\n    else:\n        ...\n```\n\nThat's `2N` round-trips to SQLite per run. Fix: one bulk `SELECT` to build a lookup dict, then batch the writes with `executemany`:\n\n```python\ndef diff(self, jobs: list[Job]) -> tuple[list[Job], list[Job]]:\n    now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat(timespec=\"seconds\")\n    cur = self.conn.cursor()\n\n    existing: dict[str, str] = {}\n    keys = [j.key for j in jobs]\n    for i in range(0, len(keys), 500):  # stay under SQLite's ~999 param limit\n        chunk = keys[i:i + 500]\n        qs = \",\".join(\"?\" * len(chunk))\n        for row in cur.execute(f\"SELECT key, content_hash FROM jobs WHERE key IN ({qs})\", chunk):\n            existing[row[\"key\"]] = row[\"content_hash\"]\n\n    new, changed, touched = [], [], []\n    insert_rows, update_rows = [], []\n    for job in jobs:\n        prev_hash = existing.get(job.key)\n        r = job.to_row()\n        if prev_hash is None:\n            new.append(job)\n            insert_rows.append({**r, \"now\": now})\n        elif prev_hash != job.content_hash:\n            changed.append(job)\n            update_rows.append({**r, \"now\": now})\n        else:\n            touched.append({\"key\": job.key, \"now\": now})\n\n    if insert_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"INSERT INTO jobs (key, source, company, external_id, title, url,\n            location, department, employment_type, posted_at, salary_range,\n            content_hash, first_seen, last_seen)\n            VALUES (:key,:source,:company,:external_id,:title,:url,:location,\n            :department,:employment_type,:posted_at,:salary_range,:content_hash,:now,:now)\"\"\",\n            insert_rows)\n    if update_rows:\n        cur.executemany(\"\"\"UPDATE jobs SET title=:title, url=:url, location=:location,\n            department=:department, employment_type=:employment_type, posted_at=:posted_at,\n            salary_range=:salary_range, content_hash=:content_hash, last_seen=:now\n            WHERE key=:key\"\"\", update_rows)\n    if touched:\n        cur.executemany(\"UPDATE jobs SET last_seen=:now WHERE key=:key\", touched)\n\n    self.conn.commit()\n    return new, changed\n```\n\nTurns `2N` round-trips into `~N/500 + 3` statements. This is the single highest-leverage change in the codebase given the source count.\n\n### 2. Redundant computation — regex recompiled per job (filters.py:11-41)\n\n`match()` calls `_compile(exclude)` and `_compile(include)` **inside the per-job loop** in `filter_jobs`:\n\n```python\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    ...\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=..., exclude=..., ...)]\n```\n\nEvery call to `match()` re-runs `re.compile()` for every keyword, for every job. With thousands of jobs and a handful of keywords, that's thousands of redundant `re.compile()` calls doing the same work. Fix — compile once, pass compiled patterns in:\n\n```python\ndef match(job: Job, *, include: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          exclude: list[re.Pattern] | None = None,\n          locations: list[str] | None = None,\n          cutoff: datetime | None = None) -> bool:\n    haystack = \" \".join((job.title, job.department, job.location))\n    if exclude and any(p.search(haystack) for p in exclude):\n        return False\n    if include and not any(p.search(haystack) for p in include):\n        return False\n    ...\n\ndef filter_jobs(jobs: list[Job], rules: dict) -> list[Job]:\n    include = _compile(rules.get(\"include_keywords\") or [])\n    exclude = _compile(rules.get(\"exclude_keywords\") or [])\n    cutoff = None\n    max_age = rules.get(\"max_age_days\")\n    if max_age:\n        cutoff = datetime.now(timezone.utc) - timedelta(days=float(max_age))\n    return [j for j in jobs if match(j, include=include, exclude=exclude,\n                                      locations=rules.get(\"locations\"), cutoff=cutoff)]\n```\n\n### 3. Redundant computation — `content_hash` computed twice per write (models.py:66-69, store.py:76-97)\n\n`Store.diff` compares `row[\"content_hash\"] != job.content_hash` (computes the SHA256), then calls `_insert`/`_update` → `job.to_row()` → accesses `self.content_hash` **again**. Cheap individually (SHA256 of a short string) but doubled unnecessarily across every new/changed job. Compute once and pass it through:\n\n```python\nh = job.content_hash\nif prev_hash is None:\n    ...\n    insert_rows.append({**job.to_row(), \"content_hash\": h, \"now\": now})\n```\n(this falls out naturally once `to_row()` isn't recomputing it inside a hot loop — minor, but free once you're already rewriting `diff`).\n\n### 4. Caching opportunity — no conditional HTTP requests\n\nPer `feat: 12h scheduled run` in the recent commits, this pipeline runs every 12h against 125 sources, several of which (`greenhouse`, `lever`, `ashby`, etc. via `_simple`) are plain unconditional `GET`s. Most of these ATS JSON APIs support `ETag`/`If-None-Match` or `Last-Modified`. Persisting the `ETag` per source (e.g. in the existing `meta` table, keyed by `f\"etag:{ats}:{company}\"`) and sending `If-None-Match` would let unchanged boards short-circuit to a `304` instead of transferring and reparsing the full payload — meaningful savings at 125 sources × 2 runs/day, especially for the large boards (Amazon/Microsoft/Apple pull thousands of rows even when nothing changed).\n\n```python\nasync def _get_json(client, url, *, store=None, cache_key=None, **kw):\n    headers = dict(kw.pop(\"headers\", {}) or {})\n    if store and cache_key and (etag := store.get_meta(f\"etag:{cache_key}\")):\n        headers[\"If-None-Match\"] = etag\n    r = await _request(client, url, headers=headers, **kw)\n    if r.status_code == 304:\n        return None  # caller treats as \"no change\"\n    if store and cache_key and \"ETag\" in r.headers:\n        store.set_meta(f\"etag:{cache_key}\", r.headers[\"ETag\"])\n    return r.json()\n```\nThis is a bigger structural change (threading `store` into fetchers) — worth doing only if the 12h-cadence bandwidth/latency actually matters to you; flagging it as an opportunity rather than prescribing it.\n\n### 5. Memory leaks\n\nNothing that qualifies as a real leak — this is a one-shot CLI process per run (`pipeline.run` / `agent.py` subcommands), not a long-lived server, so nothing has the lifetime to leak across requests. Resource handling is actually solid: `Store` and `httpx.AsyncClient` are both used via context managers / `finally`-closed everywhere I checked (store.py:52-53, fetchers.py:1019-1023, agent.py's `with _store(...)` usages).\n\nThe one thing worth naming as a *working-set* concern rather than a leak: every `Job.raw` dict (fetchers.py, e.g. Greenhouse's full posting payload, Apple's hydration blob fields) is held in memory for the full run and only dropped in `to_row()` right before the DB write. At tens of thousands of jobs across 125 sources, that's real peak memory, but it's bounded and released at process exit — not a leak, just something to know about if `concurrency` in `sources.yaml` is pushed much higher than 8.\n\n### Priority order\n1. `Store.diff` batching — highest impact, directly proportional to your 125-source scale.\n2. Regex precompilation in `filters.py` — trivial fix, real waste on every run.\n3. ETag caching — worth it only if you care about the 12h-cadence bandwidth/latency; more invasive.\n4. `content_hash` double-compute — free cleanup, do it while touching `diff` anyway.\n\nWant me to implement #1 and #2 now? They're small, self-contained, and don't touch the fetcher contracts.\n",
